storyInfo: Skadi receives guidance from her contact, disguises herself as a wandering singer, and prepares to infiltrate Sal Viento. But her eyes are not alone on Sal Viento, as Iberia's Inquisitors are watching too.

attributes.content: Skadi.
You've fallen, Skadi. The old you could've made chunks out of them with just a touch.
Mister José, I am not that bloody.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: Hard to say. You've changed, then. You even gave them a chance to escape.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Possibly.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: What wind blew you back here again? Why were they waiting to spring you—something to do with me?
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: I don't know.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: I hear you're not in our line of work anymore. Joined some... pharma company? What are you shirking good, decent work for to tromp around these rundown outskirts again?
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: You're well-informed, Mister José. This time I need you to help me out.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.text: The old man licks his rolling paper, and pulls out some second-rate tobacco from his pouch.

attributes.content: Several years have come and gone. Here I thought you'd folded, seeing as you went through plenty of Kazimierz bounty hunters. This far out from Kazimierz, and I could still hear word of what you'd been up to.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Always thought you only knew how to make big ruckuses.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: But you've been quiet as this now.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: You came roadrollering in all the way from Minos country like a tow truck, just to find me? Go on, then, tell me what you want.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: I need to get to Sal Viento.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: Sal... Viento?
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Don't tell me. Even you've never heard of the place?
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: No, I've heard. Out of all us information peddlers, only I must've heard. The question's you—what makes you want to go there?
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: There's nothing there anymore. Few decades ago... close to nothing left after.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: So close to such a vast patch of ocean, and you think anything'd be left? No better than bare frames left, letting the wind and all through.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Many bounty hunters wanting to get up to those abandoned cities, just like beastlings pouncing on a rotting burdenbeast corpse.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: All of them thinking there's still meat they can pick off. They don't know whatever they swallow there might as well be a batch of poison.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Iberia. All of them think this unspeaking Iberia's just like Kazimierz and Gaul, treasure all over the map.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Hah, there's nothing there at all. When a place has nothing at all, it's likelier than all it could have anything.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: So do you tell those bounty hunters anything?
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: If they ask me to sell info, I'll sell it. As far as ones like me go, whether those folks come back or don't, it's all business.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Fact is, they don't come back at all. Not one ever comes back.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Two weeks ago, a team came to me. Lackeys of the 'Daggerhorn.'
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: He had equipment leagues better than all these runts lying around. Very experienced too. Brought more than ten with him. Still haven't seen them again yet.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Very many wonder about where they went. They could've been caught by the Penal Battalion, or it could've been the Iberian Defensa's doing, but I've heard tell of a different possibility.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Over there be... monsters.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Oh.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: Or it was the Inquisition that got 'em. I don't know what's a more wretched end.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Monsters or people, my sword draws little distinction. There are only those who block my way, and those who don't.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: Alright, alright. You can't be going to Sal Viento for a holiday, that much's for sure.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: I need to find someone.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: What poor bastard has your wrath this time?
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: This time's different. It's my... It's someone I knew from before.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: Before you even knew me?
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Much before.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: Here I thought they'd all left. Or died. At least, that's what you told me back in those days.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: That's why I'm searching. There's a few things I need to figure out.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: You've been searching for quite some years, yeah?
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: That whole ruckus from last time couldn't have been for any knights' treasure's sakes.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: You told me before. People ought to move forward.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: Did you bring a treasure map with you?
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: What?
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: There're many, some of them even old hands. They travel the barrens, traveling and traveling, and forget where they wanted to go, or what they were even looking for.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: They just keep on traveling. They don't know starvation, they don't know exhaustion.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Until the barrenlands do them in.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: They were too weak.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: Weak? No matter how much stronger, a hunter could still never conquer the boundless barrenlands. So many hunters die for no sure reason out on the road, and don't even know what they're searching for come their deaths—that's not an ending that suits you.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Why are you telling me all this?
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: As if I've never told you before? They wouldn't rival even the tiniest Ægir machine.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: You're strong. So did you save my son's life?
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: I'm sorry.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: Don't say sorry! I'm not trying to flog you here. I'm trying to get you thinking. It's you who hasn't forgiven yourself, not me.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: I only regret that I didn't break his legs, stop him following an old papá in his old tracks. Nothing to do with you.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: You say you came from the sea. I've never heard of any other sea than the one in Iberia. You're someone I don't know.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: So what about you? Is there no one you don't know?
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Because that's the kind that killed my son. Someone you don't even know.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: That's the sort of thing I'm afraid of.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: Never mind it. At least the people you talk about wouldn't spend day and night plotting to kill me. What are you thinking of doing in Sal Viento?
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: I have a friend who's been taken there.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: Strange, that.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Take this. Map.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Alright. What do I need to give you?
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: Give me?
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: You sell intel. One thing for another. You've given me information, I'll give you what you need.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: (Flicks cigarette ash)
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Let me think... That year you brought my young Juan's body back, you handed him to me. Head and arms all still attached to him. So, now we're even.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Mister José, my greatest thanks.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: I'll be going, then. Take care.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: Stop! Are you in such a hurry to get yourself killed?!
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Hm?
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: Hey. Tell me—has anyone ever said anything like that to you before?
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: No.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: Then you need somebody to tell you well.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: You're strolling straight into an Iberian city dressed in all your bounty hunter clothes?
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Yes.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: You really haven't changed, Skadi. Here I am parching my mouth, and I might as well be the wind for all the good telling you anything does.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: The Iberian Defensa'd have you ten times over for looking like that!
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: And how much time are you ready to waste on them? How much longer can the person you're looking for wait? Iberians aren't like these lousy bounty hunters. They're not that easy to break clean of.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: You want to suggest something to me.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: I can lend you a few things. Take this harp.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Harp?
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: Can you play? I remember you played before.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: I can.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: Good, all the better. Would be fine if you couldn't, long as you pulled off the act.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Change into these too.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: What clothes are these? They're very strange.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: Whether you're used to them isn't the point. Iberians are.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: From now on, you're the wandering singer Skadi.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Go where you want now, singer. Follow the map, go by the waterways, and you'll get there soon enough. This you can do, Ægir.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Farewell, Mister José.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: Skadi!
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Don't you die out there. You have to die with someone, someone you know.
attributes.name: Old José

attributes.content: Right.
attributes.name: Skadi

attributes.content: Help—Help me!
attributes.name: Bounty Hunter

attributes.content: What are these things... they—they're tangling me, they won't let go! Chopping them apart doesn't even work. Is the entire coast all monsters like this?
attributes.name: Bounty Hunter

attributes.content: Hey—get away, get the hell away!
attributes.name: Bounty Hunter

attributes.content: I wouldn't have come if I goddamn knew! Ja pierdolę, 'Yellow Smog,' bastard, if only you weren't so useless to get hoodwinked back then, would I still be stuck picking up garbage out here?!
attributes.name: Bounty Hunter

attributes.content: Skurwysyny, if I'm not dead by the end of this I'll wish I was! Goddamned Iberia! Country of the actual goddamned!
attributes.name: Bounty Hunter

attributes.content: What—What the hell was that? Turning them all to paste in one shot?
attributes.name: Bounty Hunter

attributes.content: Huff... huff. Whatever it was, at least it lets me live another day—
attributes.name: Bounty Hunter

attributes.content: Ugh—
attributes.name: Bounty Hunter

attributes.content: You. You're not leaving.
And—And who are you? Where the hell does Iberia get all these freaks from?
attributes.name: Bounty Hunter

attributes.content: Second time. Iberia forbids the spreading of rumors. The next you move to speak, be much more careful.
What? Look at that getup, that weapon—
attributes.name: Bounty Hunter

attributes.content: Holy shit. You, you're... that's it, I'm done for, I'm...
attributes.name: Bounty Hunter

attributes.content: Commander. The coast is clean now.
This place is void of all living—er, excepting this outsider who can't stand still and stinks to high Heaven.
What did you see?
Please, I haven't done anything! I swear it, I, I was only lost, I was too careless to end up here, I didn't mean to...
attributes.name: Bounty Hunter

attributes.content: Look, I have gold coins, and plenty of other stuff too, damnit, I've lost so much... Take this money, this equipment, all of it, I just beg you to let me go!
attributes.name: Bounty Hunter

attributes.content: Gather your scraps. When the Commander asks you a question, it's not to hear you blather, outsider.
Question? What question? I swear, honor, I wouldn't dare ask questions... I've got no questions, I guarantee...
attributes.name: Bounty Hunter

attributes.content: I beg you, honor, I don't want... Don't take me... I'd be better off if I just died!
attributes.name: Bounty Hunter

attributes.content: Casting yourself into the sea in front of me? Do you still think it's not too late?
That sword... my hand... too close... wargh...
attributes.name: Bounty Hunter

attributes.content: Now, have you regained some sense? You outsiders are as good as insects in the weeds, hearts avaricious and blackened, yet always so quick to fall to pieces.
Ugh, ah... I'm not running anywhere, honor, I'll tell you anything.
attributes.name: Bounty Hunter

attributes.content: Good. I do not like repeating my questions. This will therefore be the final time.
What did you see on the coast?
I, I... *cough* *cough*... I saw monsters.
attributes.name: Bounty Hunter

attributes.content: How many of you came?
Originally twelve... uh, counting the guide, we're thirteen total.
attributes.name: Bounty Hunter

attributes.content: Commander. He's not lying. I've found the corpses myself along the coast.
Hey. What use will crying be for you now? If it weren't for you all intruding, they wouldn't have sought you out. When you violate the law, you should anticipate the costs.
That said, twelve have died... They've been proliferating in number, all along the way here.
They can't have gone too far from their nest.
This serves to show your judgment was sound. The closer one approaches, the more numerous they are. There is surely something amiss going on in that town!
You may depart.
And this fellow? He has seen much he shouldn't have.
Spare... Spare me! I've told you everything I can! Sir, Commander, your honor... ohh, mama...
attributes.name: Bounty Hunter

attributes.content: What... did you see?
We made an agreement.
attributes.name: Bishop

attributes.content: I do not know what sense lies in such conduct.
You agreed to it.
attributes.name: Bishop

attributes.content: Agreed? Pledged—(Bones and flesh chafe against each other.)—promised? To prior be granted an act, and afterwards to accomplish one different?
No.
To such requests of yours, I will respond. No agreement, nor promise.
A response... but of course.
attributes.name: Bishop

attributes.content: Honorable herald—
attributes.name: Bishop

attributes.content: That you will to respond is already my honor.
attributes.name: Bishop
